Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in JavaScript is a programming paradigm used to organize and structure code using objects and classes. It helps developers model real-world entities and build scalable, reusable, and maintainable applications. In JavaScript, everything revolves around objects, which are collections of properties and methods that represent data and behavior. With the introduction of ES6, JavaScript provided a clearer syntax for classes, making OOP easier to implement while still using its prototype-based inheritance system internally.

OOP in JavaScript is based on four main principles: encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, and abstraction. Encapsulation refers to bundling data and methods together and restricting direct access to certain details, ensuring better data security. Inheritance allows one class or object to acquire properties and methods from another, promoting code reuse and reducing redundancy. Polymorphism enables methods to perform different tasks based on the object that invokes them, allowing flexibility and dynamic behavior. Abstraction focuses on hiding complex implementation details and exposing only the necessary features to the user, simplifying interaction with the system.

Using OOP concepts in JavaScript makes code more modular, organized, and easier to debug or extend. It is widely used in modern web development, especially in frameworks like React, Angular, and Node.js, where applications are built using reusable components and structured architecture. Overall, OOP in JavaScript provides a systematic approach to software development, helping developers create efficient and maintainable applications.